[start section id="20112"]

#1 Stage I (pT1, N0, M0) rectal cancer
Ms. Hogan has had a very early-stage rectal cancer resected.  I reviewed the findings on pathology with her and her partner today and reassured her that given this early-stage disease, her outcome would be expected to be very good after surgical resection, and that there is no need for adjuvant therapy in this setting.  Ms. Hogan and her partner expressed understanding, and she is planning to undergo takedown of her ostomy on November 11.
As far as surveillance, I think that her risk is low enough that we can see her every four to six-months with a history, physical exam, and perhaps a CEA.  We may perform further imaging in the form of a CT-scan on a yearly-or-so basis, both for surveillance but as well to ensure the stability of the superior mediastinal mass which raises the possibility of thymoma.
All of this was discussed with Ms. Hogan and her partner, and they expressed understanding.  I will see her back in four to six-months with a history, physical, and CEA.
I have discussed this case at length with Dr. Davis, my supervising oncologist for the day, who was essential in the formation of the assessment and plan.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at Ankeny County Memorial Hospital.

[end section id="20112"]

