[start section id="20103"]

Ms. Hogan is a very pleasant 49-year-old female with the following oncologic history (for further diagnostic details, please see my note dated August 5, 2010):
1.  July 2010, screening colonoscopy reveals a concerning mass 15-cm from the anal verge.  Biopsy is consistent with intramucosal adenocarcinoma.  Patient is asymptomatic at this time.
2.  August  2010, Mr. Hogan referred to Ankeny County Memorial Hospital for further evaluation.  Flexible sigmoidoscopy reveals obvious mass concerning for malignancy and further staging including an EUS reveals T1, N0 rectal cancer and no evidence of distant disease on imaging including a chest, abdomen, and pelvis CT-scan.
3.  August 24, 2010, Dr. Depriest performs a low-anterior resection with temporary diverting ileostomy.  Pathology review reveals a 1.5- x 1.5- x 0.6-cm ulcerated mass composed of mildly differentiated adenocarcinoma.  Margins were negative, and 19 regional lymph nodes were also negative making this a (pT1, N0, M0) rectal cancer.
Ms. Hogan returns to clinic today in the postoperative setting.  Her postoperative course was complicated by wound dehiscence and infection for which she is on antibiotics and packing the wound.  This has been the major limiting step in her recovery, and she states that her ostomy is functioning well.  She frankly denies fevers, chills, abdominal pain, nausea, or vomiting at this time.

[end section id="20103"]

